    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-11-16T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-11-16T13:00:00-05:00" n="155"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d155">
                <head>155. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Cuba</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d155fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 737.00/11–1658. Confidential; Priority.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Havana</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1958-11-16T13:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 16, 1958—1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>507. For <persName corresp="#p_RRRJ1">Rubottom</persName>. At conference with
                    President <persName corresp="#p_BZF1">Batista</persName> November 15 he stated
                    approximately 100 ill-equipped soldiers are guarding the isolated aquaduct at
                    Yateras and are bait for rebels who would like to capture aquaduct for
                    propaganda purposes.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_BZF1">Batista</persName> suggests following alternatives: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>US sell adequate arms to <gloss target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> troops
                            for defense of aquaduct at Yateras.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> withdraw troops, leaving civilian
                            personnel. But aquaduct must be provided with radio communication to
                            naval base and to army headquarters at Guantanamo City. There are many
                                <gloss target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> troops in surrounding area
                            subject to emergency summons.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>If US will not agree to numbers one and two above, <gloss
                                target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> will leave the soldiers for protection
                            even though they are poorly equipped and are a [?] sacrifice.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>In the light of recent events which include loss of American lives, sabotage of
                    American property, extortion of Americans, kidnapping of Americans, and the fact
                    that the <gloss target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> is the only recourse for
                    protection, please advise what reply I am to give the President.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d155fn2">In telegram 267 to Havana, November 17, the Department
                        indicated that alternatives 1 and 2 were unacceptable and instructed the
                        Ambassador to inform President <persName corresp="#p_BZF1"
                            >Batista</persName> that the U.S. Government desired the third
                        alternative. (<hi rend="italic">ibid</hi>., 737.00/11–1758) In telegram 517
                        from Havana, November 18, <persName corresp="#p_SEET1">Smith</persName>
                        reported that he had so informed Guell. (<hi rend="italic">ibid</hi>.,
                        737.00/11–1858)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SEET1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Smith</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
